        "tetractys": {
          "title": "Tetractys",
          "slug": "tetractys",
          "schema": "article",
          "template": "article",
          "publishedAt": "2026-03-29T21:14",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-30T02:05:09.519Z",
          "content": {
            "title": "Tetractys",
            "publishedAt": "2026-03-29T21:14",
            "heroText": "\"Probably the coolest thing you have ever built.\" - Wife",
            "excerpt": "\"Probably the coolest thing you've ever built.\" - Wife",
            "body": "<p>In an era of bloated Content Management Systems (CMS) and complex cloud infrastructures, a new architectural philosophy is emerging. Tetractys—named after the triangular figure consisting of ten points arranged in four rows—is not just another website builder. It is a \"decoupled\" engine designed to return structural integrity to the web.</p>\n\n<h2>The Problem with Modern Web Management</h2>\n\n<p>Traditional CMS platforms often suffer from \"Substance-Form Entanglement.\" When your content (the substance) is trapped inside the same database or logic as your design (the form), scaling becomes a nightmare. Any change to the visual layer risks corrupting the data layer, and vice versa.</p>\n\n<h2>The Tetractys Solution: Atomic Decoupling</h2>\n\n<p>Tetractys is unique because it treats a website as a series of \"Atomic Units.\" As seen in the Landing Page Schema, every element—from a simple \"Logo Title\" to a complex \"Workflow Step\"—is defined as a distinct data point before a single line of CSS is ever considered.</p>\n\n<p>1. Schema-First Integrity\n\n<p>Unlike other platforms where you \"drag and drop\" elements, Tetractys begins with a Registry of Schemas. You define the data requirements—the what—and the engine dynamically builds the administrative interface for you. This ensures that no matter how the design evolves, the underlying content remains clean, structured, and reusable.</p>\n\n<p>2. Form Follows Substance\n\n<p>By using a Template Registry, Tetractys allows developers to craft visual identities using pure HTML and CSS, binding them to schema fields via simple {{tags}}. This decoupling means you can swap out an entire website's look in seconds without migrating a single row of a database.</p>\n\n<p>3. GitHub-Native Workflow\n\n<p>One of the most unique aspects of Tetractys is its reliance on the GitHub API. There is no proprietary cloud database. Your content, your schemas, and your templates live in your own repository. This provides built-in version control, collaborative branching, and a level of transparency that \"black box\" CMS platforms cannot match.</p>\n\n<p>System Performance: The Zero-Server Advantage\n\n<p>Because Tetractys generates a static output from its JSON-based logic, it is inherently faster and more secure. With 99+ Lighthouse scores and Global CDN readiness, the engine eliminates the need for expensive backends. It is \"Zero-Server\" architecture at its finest.</p>\n\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n\n<p>Tetractys is built for those who believe that the web should be as organized as it is beautiful. By separating the \"Atomic\" components of a site from its visual representation, it provides a \"Static Site Power\" that is truly developer-first. It is not just a tool for building sites; it is a framework for architecting the future of content.</p>",
            "footerText": "(c) 2026 / Dean Haddock"
          }
        }
      }
